The Department of State Security Service, (DSS) and the Economic and  Financial Crimes Commission (EFCC), have debunked reports of an alleged arrest of the acting chairman of the EFCC, Ibrahim Magu. There was anxiety in the media and across the nation’s capital  yesterday when news of the reported arrest of Magu by the DSS broke  over some reported cases of infractions in the recoveries made by the  commission. In a statement which offered an insight into what had transpired,   the EFCC spokesperson, Dele Oyewale, said Magu, on Monday, 6 July,  2020, only honoured an invitation by a Presidential Panel reviewing the activities of the EFCC, at the Banquet Hall wing of the  Presidential Villa, Abuja. Oyewale, the EFCC spokesperson explained that Magu was served the  invitation to the panel while on his way to the Force Headquarters,  Abuja for a meeting. He stated that the EFCC’s boss was neither arrested nor forced to  honour the invitation, as a member of a legal team from the EFCC is also with him on the Panel. Similarly, the DSS stated that Magu was never arrested by the service. The DSS spokesperson, Dr Peter Afunanya said: “The DSS wishes to  inform the public that it did not arrest Ibrahim Magu, acting chairman  of the EFCC as has been reported by sections of the media. “The service has since, 6 July, 2020, been inundated with enquiries  over the alleged arrest.” Recall that the Attorney General of the Federation (AGF), Abubakar  Malami had accused Magu of gross infractions in one of his memos.